    <h2 id="three-groups">The Three Verb Groups</h2>
    <p><strong>Group 1 (五段 godan):</strong> Verbs whose stems end in a consonant. Examples: 飲む (nomu, drink), 書く (kaku, write), 話す (hanasu, speak). These conjugate by changing the final vowel sound.</p>
    <p><strong>Group 2 (一段 ichidan):</strong> Verbs ending in -iru or -eru. Examples: 食べる (taberu, eat), 見る (miru, see). These conjugate simply by dropping -ru and adding the conjugation ending.</p>
    <p><strong>Group 3 (不規則 irregular):</strong> Only two verbs — する (suru, to do) and 来る (kuru, to come). These must be memorized individually.</p>

    <h2 id="polite">Polite Form (ます)</h2>
    <p>The polite form is used in most social situations. Group 1: change the final -u to -imasu (飲む→飲みます). Group 2: drop -ru, add -masu (食べる→食べます). Irregular: する→します, 来る→来ます. Try our <a href="/japanese/tools/verb-conjugator/">Verb Conjugator</a> to see all forms.</p>

    <h2 id="te-form">Te-Form</h2>
    <p>Te-form is essential for making requests, connecting sentences, and forming progressive tense. Group 2 is easy: drop -ru, add -te (食べて). Group 1 follows patterns based on the ending consonant: -mu/-nu/-bu → -nde, -ku → -ite, -su → -shite, -u/-tsu/-ru → -tte. The irregular verbs: して, 来て.</p>

    <h2 id="past-negative">Past and Negative</h2>
    <p>Past tense follows the same consonant patterns as te-form but ends in -ta/-da instead. Negative form: Group 1 changes final -u to -anai (飲まない), Group 2 drops -ru and adds -nai (食べない). Irregular: しない, 来ない. Practice all conjugations with our <a href="/japanese/tools/verb-conjugator/">Verb Conjugator</a>.</p>

